result.execSummary:
On one or more charges in this case, Donell Mitchell was found not guilty by reason of mental disease or defect. The defendant was found guilty of actually committing the crime(s) charged, but was also found not to be legally responsible under Wis. Stats. 971.165 for committing the crime(s) because of the defendant's mental condition. The legal effect of a finding of not guilty by reason of mental disease or defect is that the court must commit the defendant to the custody of the Department of Health and Family Services.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Donell Mitchell in court with attorney Darryl Everett Smith.  James C Griffin appeared for Tyrone St. Junior for the State of Wisconsin.  Written Waiver of Trial by Jury as to Phase II is filed and accepted by the court.  Upon request of both the state and defense the court will use the report of Dr. Rawski dated April 10, 2016 to make a finding for the defendant of not guilty by reason of mental disease, that at the time of the incident the defendant did lack substantial capacity to appreciate the wrongfulness of his behavior and conform his conduct to the requirements of the law.  The court orders a Conditional Release Plan to be prepared by WCS.  All conditions of bail to continue, defendant to continue to take all prescribed medications.  The defendant lacks substantial capacity to understand and apply the advantages, disadvantages, and alternatives to treatment.  Atty Smith will contact WCS.  Case is adjourned to 6-7-2016 at 8:15 for return of plan.
